#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:29
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you're looking for a way to synchronize files and folders between computers automatically, `lsyncd` is a pretty great option. The only downside for beginners? You have to configure everything at the command line, and text files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:31
#, no-wrap
msgid "Even so, it is a program worth learning for any sysadmin.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:33
#, no-wrap
msgid "The best description of `lsyncd`, comes from its own man page. Slightly paraphrased, `lsyncd` is a light-weight live mirror solution that is not hard to install. It does not  require new filesystems or block devices, and does not hamper local filesystem performance. In short, it mirrors files.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:35
#, no-wrap
msgid "`lsyncd` watches a local directory tree's event monitor interface (inotify). It aggregates and combines events for a few seconds, and then spawns one (or more) process(es) to synchronize the changes. By default this is `rsync`.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:37
#, no-wrap
msgid "For the purposes of this guide, you will call the system with the original files the \"source\", and the one that we are synchronizing to will be the \"target\". It is actually possible to completely mirror a server using `lsyncd` by very carefully specifying directories and files that you want to synchronize. It's pretty sweet!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:39
#, no-wrap
msgid "For remote syncing, you will also want to set up [Rocky Linux SSH Public Private Key Pairs](../security/ssh_public_private_keys.md). The examples here use SSH (port 22).\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:40
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing `lsyncd`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:43
#, no-wrap
msgid "There are actually two ways to install `lsyncd`. We will include them both here. The RPM tends to lag behind the source packages by a little, but only by a little. The version installed by the RPM method at the time of this writing is 2.2.2-9, whereas the source code version is now at 2.2.3. That said, we want to give you both options and let you choose.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:44
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing `lsyncd` - RPM Method"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:47
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing the RPM version is not hard. The only thing you will need to install first is the EPEL software repository from Fedora. This can be done with a single command:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:49
#, no-wrap
msgid "`dnf install -y epel-release`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:51
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then, we just need to install `lsyncd` and any missing dependencies will be installed along with it:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:53
#, no-wrap
msgid "`dnf install lsyncd`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:55
#, no-wrap
msgid "Set up the service to start on boot, but don't start it just yet:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:57
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:242
#, no-wrap
msgid "`systemctl enable lsyncd`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:59
#, no-wrap
msgid "That's it!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:60
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing `lsyncd` - Source Method"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:63
#, no-wrap
msgid "Installing from source is not as bad is it sounds. Just follow this guide and you will be up and running in no time!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:64
#, no-wrap
msgid "Install Dependencies"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:67
#, no-wrap
msgid "We will need some dependencies: a few that are required by `lsyncd` itself, and a few that are required to build packages from source. Use this command on your Rocky Linux computer to ensure you have the dependencies you need. If you are going to be building from source, it is a good idea to have all of the development tools installed:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:69
#, no-wrap
msgid "`dnf groupinstall 'Development Tools'`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:71
#, no-wrap
msgid "!!! warning \"For Rocky Linux 9.0\"\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:73
#, no-wrap
msgid "    `lsyncd` has been fully tested in Rocky Linux 9.0, and will work as expected. In order to get all of the needed dependencies installed, however, you will need to enable an additional repository:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:77
#, no-wrap
msgid "    ```\n"
"    dnf config-manager --enable crb\n"
"    ```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:79
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Doing this in 9 before the next steps, will allow you to finish the build without backtracking.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:81
#, no-wrap
msgid "And here are the dependencies we need for `lsyncd` itself, and its build process:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:83
#, no-wrap
msgid "`dnf install lua lua-libs lua-devel cmake unzip wget rsync`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:84
#, no-wrap
msgid "Download `lsyncd` And Build It"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:87
#, no-wrap
msgid "Next we need the source code:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:89
#, no-wrap
msgid "`wget https://github.com/axkibe/lsyncd/archive/master.zip`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:91
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now uncompress the master.zip file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:93
#, no-wrap
msgid "`unzip master.zip`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:95
#, no-wrap
msgid "This will create a directory called \"lsyncd-master\". We need to change to this directory and create a directory called build:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:97
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cd lsyncd-master`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:99
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:232
#: ../src/docs/guides/database/database_mariadb-server.md:40
#: ../src/docs/guides/file_sharing/secure_ftp_server_vsftpd.md:156
#: ../src/docs/guides/security/generating_ssl_keys_lets_encrypt.md:44
#: ../src/docs/guides/web/apache_hardened_webserver/ossec-hids.md:152
#, no-wrap
msgid "And then:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:101
#, no-wrap
msgid "`mkdir build`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:103
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now change directories again so that you are in the build directory:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:105
#, no-wrap
msgid "`cd build`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:107
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now run these commands:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:108
#, no-wrap
msgid "cmake ..\n"
"make\n"
"make install\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:115
#, no-wrap
msgid "When done, you will have the `lsyncd` binary installed and ready for use in */usr/local/bin*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:116
#, no-wrap
msgid "`lsyncd` Systemd Service"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:119
#, no-wrap
msgid "With the RPM install method, the systemd service will be installed for you, but if you choose to install from source, you will need to create the systemd service. While you can start the binary without the systemd service, we want to ensure that it *does* start on boot. If not, a server reboot would stop your synchronization effort and if you forgot to start it again, which is highly likely. That could be very embarrassing for any systems administrator!\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:121
#, no-wrap
msgid "Creating the systemd service is not terribly difficult, though, and will save you time in the long run.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ####
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:122
#, no-wrap
msgid "Create The `lsyncd` Service File"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:125
#, no-wrap
msgid "This file can be created anywhere, even in the root directory of your server. When created, you can move it the right location.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "`vi /root/lsyncd.service`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:129
#, no-wrap
msgid "The contents of this file should be:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:130
#, no-wrap
msgid "[Unit]\n"
"Description=Live Syncing (Mirror) Daemon\n"
"After=network.target\n\n"
"[Service]\n"
"Restart=always\n"
"Type=simple\n"
"Nice=19\n"
"ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/lsyncd -nodaemon -pidfile /run/lsyncd.pid /etc/lsyncd.conf\n"
"ExecReload=/bin/kill -HUP $MAINPID\n"
"PIDFile=/run/lsyncd.pid\n\n"
"[Install]\n"
"WantedBy=multi-user.target\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:147
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now let's install the file you just made to the correct location:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:149
#, no-wrap
msgid "`install -Dm0644 /root/lsyncd.service /usr/lib/systemd/system/lsyncd.service`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:151
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finally, reload the `systemctl` daemon so that systemd will \"see\" the new service file:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:153
#, no-wrap
msgid "`systemctl daemon-reload`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:154
#, no-wrap
msgid "`lsyncd` Configuration"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:157
#, no-wrap
msgid "Whichever method you choose for installing `lsyncd`, you will need a configuration file: */etc/lsyncd.conf*. The next section will tell you how to build a configuration file, and test it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:158
#, no-wrap
msgid "Sample Configuration For Testing"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:161
#, no-wrap
msgid "Here's an example of a simplistic configuration file that synchronizes */home* to another computer. Our target computer is going to be a local IP address: *192.168.1.40*\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:162
#, no-wrap
msgid "  settings {\n"
"   logfile = \"/var/log/lsyncd.log\",\n"
"   statusFile = \"/var/log/lsyncd-status.log\",\n"
"   statusInterval = 20,\n"
"   maxProcesses = 1\n"
"   }\n\n"
"sync {\n"
"   default.rsyncssh,\n"
"   source=\"/home\",\n"
"   host=\"root@192.168.1.40\",\n"
"   excludeFrom=\"/etc/lsyncd.exclude\",\n"
"   targetdir=\"/home\",\n"
"   rsync = {\n"
"     archive = true,\n"
"     compress = false,\n"
"     whole_file = false\n"
"   },\n"
"   ssh = {\n"
"     port = 22\n"
"   }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:188
#, no-wrap
msgid "Breaking down this file a bit:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"logfile\" and \"statusFile\" will be automatically created when the service starts.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"statusInterval\" is the number of seconds to wait before writing to the statusFile.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "\"maxProcesses\" is the number of processes `lsyncd` is allowed to spawn. Honestly, unless you are running this on a super busy computer, 1 process is enough.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "In the sync section \"default.rsyncssh\" says to use rsync over SSH\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"source=\" is the directory path we are syncing from.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"host=\" is our target computer that we are syncing to.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"excludeFrom=\" tells `lsyncd` where the exclusions file is. It must exist, but can be empty.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "The \"targetdir=\" is the target directory we are sending files to. In most cases this will be equal to the source, but not always.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "Then we have the \"rsync =\" section, and these are the options that we are running rsync with.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:199
#, no-wrap
msgid "Finally we have the \"ssh =\" section, and this specifies the SSH port that is listening on the target computer.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:201
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you are adding more than one directory to sync, then you need to repeat the entire \"sync\" section including all the opening and closing brackets for each directory.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:202
#, no-wrap
msgid "The lsyncd.exclude File"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:205
#, no-wrap
msgid "As noted earlier, the \"excludeFrom\" file must exist, so let's create that now:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:207
#, no-wrap
msgid "`touch /etc/lsyncd.exclude`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:209
#, no-wrap
msgid "If you were syncing the /etc folder on our computer, there would be many files and directories that you should exclude. Each excluded file or directory is listed in the file, one per line, like this:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:210
#, no-wrap
msgid "/etc/hostname\n"
"/etc/hosts\n"
"/etc/networks\n"
"/etc/fstab\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:217
#, no-wrap
msgid "Test And Turn Up"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:220
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now that everything else is set up, you can test it all. For starters, lets ensure our systemd lsyncd.service will start:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:222
#, no-wrap
msgid "`systemctl start lsyncd`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:224
#, no-wrap
msgid "If no errors appear after executing this command, check the status of the service, just to ensure:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:226
#, no-wrap
msgid "`systemctl status lsyncd`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:228
#, no-wrap
msgid "If it shows the service running, use tail to see the ends of the two log files, and ensure everything shows up OK:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:230
#, no-wrap
msgid "`tail /var/log/lsyncd.log`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:234
#, no-wrap
msgid "`tail /var/log/lsyncd-status.log`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:236
#, no-wrap
msgid "Assuming that this all looks correct, navigate to the `/home/[user]` directory, where `[user]` is a user on the computer and create a new file there with *touch*.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:238
#, no-wrap
msgid "`touch /home/[user]/testfile`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:240
#, no-wrap
msgid "Now go to the target computer and see if the file shows up. If so, everything is working as it should. Set the lsyncd.service to start on boot with:\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:244
#, no-wrap
msgid "And you are ready to go.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ##
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:245
#, no-wrap
msgid "Remember To Be Careful"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:248
#, no-wrap
msgid "Anytime you are synchronizing a set of files or directories to another computer, think carefully about the effect it will have on the target computer. If you go back to **The lsyncd.exclude File** in our example above, can you imagine what might happen if */etc/fstab* is synchronized?\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/backup/mirroring_lsyncd.md:250
#, no-wrap
msgid "For newbies, *fstab* is the file that is used to configure storage drives on any Linux computer. The disks and labels are almost certainly different. The next time the target computer was rebooted it would likely fail to boot entirely.\n"
msgstr ""

